---+ Christian Kirschner's Work

---++ Project Plan (tentative)

   * *Month 0.0 - 1.5 DATA*
      * Part 1
         * Read task description (CICLing sec. 4; IGI sec. rel. anchoring)
         * Read annotation guidebook
         * Familiarize with task
      * Part 2
         * Look into Wiktionary; structure and API access
         * Which dimensions are necessary/important to consider for a dataset?
            * This will be a core question to be discussed
         * Include Wikisaurus?
         * Develop a well-balanced reference dataset for the English relation anchoring task (maybe also for the German?) [with !ChM]
         * Update the annotation guidebook
      * Part 3
         * Annotate the data [@ChM find additional annotator(s)]
         * Evaluate the dataset [with !ChM]

   * *Month 1.5  3.0 METHOD*
      * Part 4
         * @ChM Update the anchoring framework
         * Get the framework to work, familiarize with code
         * Run the existing methods with old and new data
         * Analyze errors
            * What do we need to solve?
            * What can be improved?
            * This will be a core question to be discussed
      * Part 5
         * Try and develop heuristics
         * Try and develop new methods, ideas:
            * PPR?
            * Graph-based method (Navid?)
            * PROX?
            * Milne/Witten?

---++ GoldStandard Generation

   * On the one hand the GoldStandard should build up in a way that weaknesses of disambiguation algorithms can be detected, on the other hand it should be quite representative. Therefore we are going to use the following criteria:
      * Part of speech
      * Relations
      * Number of candidates
      * Labels





